    <h2>6. Factory-Direct vs Dealer: When to Use Which</h2>
    <p>Understanding when factory-direct purchasing makes sense — and when a local dealer is actually the better choice — is key to getting the best value.</p>

    <h3>Factory-Direct Makes Sense When:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>You're buying multiple units</strong> — whether equipping a new bakery or stocking up for a chain, volume gives you leverage and the logistics cost is spread across units</li>
      <li><strong>You need customization</strong> — non-standard dimensions, special heating configurations, branding, or integration with specific production lines</li>
      <li><strong>You're close to the manufacturing cluster</strong> — if you're in Delhi and the factory is in Naraina, the logistics advantage disappears and the savings are real</li>
      <li><strong>You're buying a known model with no need for demo or hand-holding</strong> — you've seen the product, you know what you want, you just want the best price</li>
      <li><strong>You're a chain buyer or repeat purchaser</strong> — factories will prioritize relationship buyers and offer better terms over time</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>A Local Dealer Makes Sense When:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>You need to see demos</strong> — dealers often have showrooms; factories rarely do unless pre-arranged</li>
      <li><strong>You need fast local service</strong> — a dealer with on-the-ground technicians can often respond faster than factory service teams</li>
      <li><strong>You're buying one unit of something complex</strong> — the logistics coordination, installation, and warranty management cost of going direct may exceed the savings</li>
      <li><strong>You're in a Tier-2 or Tier-3 city</strong> — the freight cost and service gap from buying direct can wipe out the price savings</li>
    </ul>

