    <h2>7. Understanding MOQ (Minimum Order Quantities)</h2>
    <p>Minimum order quantities vary significantly by manufacturer type and product category. Here's what to expect:</p>

    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Manufacturer Type</th><th>Typical MOQ</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Small Indian manufacturer (custom fabrication)</td><td>1 unit</td><td>MOQ is rarely an issue; custom = 1 unit minimum</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Mid-size Indian manufacturer (standard products)</td><td>1–3 units</td><td>Most will sell single units; better terms at 3+</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Large Indian manufacturer (OEM supply)</td><td>5–10 units</td><td>OEM customers; single unit orders may be declined</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Imported equipment (direct from Asian manufacturer)</td><td>10–20 units or 1 container</td><td>Direct import only viable for chains or importers</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Indian importer of foreign brands</td><td>1 unit</td><td>No MOQ; but pay importer's margin</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>For most independent bakery owners buying 1–3 units, Indian manufacturers and importers of foreign brands are the realistic options. If you're setting up a chain (5+ locations) or an industrial bakery, you have genuine leverage with larger factories and can negotiate significantly below list price.</p>

    <h2>8. Customization Options: What Indian Manufacturers Can Do</h2>
    <p>One underappreciated advantage of working with Indian manufacturers is their flexibility on customization. Unlike buying an imported product where you get what the catalog says, Indian manufacturers will routinely modify:</p>

    <h3>Ovens</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Deck dimensions (tray size — 40×60 cm, 45×65 cm, 60×80 cm, custom)</li>
      <li>Number of decks (add or remove chambers from standard configurations)</li>
      <li>Gas vs electric vs dual-fuel configurations</li>
      <li>Steam injection addition to standard models</li>
      <li>Double-glazed doors for better heat retention</li>
      <li>Digital vs analogue controls</li>
      <li>Branding and colour finishes (extra cost)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Mixers</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Bowl sizes (non-standard capacities available from most manufacturers)</li>
      <li>Motor power upgrades for denser doughs</li>
      <li>Variable speed drives instead of fixed-speed gearboxes</li>
      <li>Custom attachment types (hook, paddle, whip in non-standard sizes)</li>
      <li>Timer controls and automatic shutoff</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Stainless Steel Fabrication</h3>
    <p>For custom stainless steel items — prep tables, display cases, bread racks, modular kitchen modules — Indian fabricators will build to your exact millimetre-level specifications with a 2–4 week lead time. This is one area where Indian manufacturing is genuinely world-class in terms of flexibility.</p>

